elements.name: Pattern Overview
elements.documentation: This section presents information about the "officialness" of a pattern (for lack of a better term). This section would help the pattern user and pattern submitter distinguish between institutionally supported patterns and patterns submitted by individuals who solved one-off problems for specific use cases that have not yet been folded into the greater pattern set.

elements.name: Pattern Implementation
elements.documentation:
This section contains the technical description and examples of the pattern, at the abstract ontology level and at the specific SysML level. It also describes other implementation information, such as tooling, open questions, and tricks.

Here we describe the elements that make up the pattern, their relationships, responsibilities, and collaborations. The solution does not describe a particular concrete design or implementation. Instead, the pattern provides an abstract description of a design problem and how a general arrangement of elements solves it. The solution is presented in modeling language independent terms and in its SysML embedding.

elements.name: Get the target of the Directed Association
elements.documentation: This Viewpoint gets the "target" of directed association relationships. The expected input is an association or list of associations, and the expected output is the target or list of targets. This is complex since a directed association is not of type UML::DirectedRelationship so it has no property like "target". However, when you create an association you also create two properties: one for each end of the association. An association owns these properties by default, but for directed associations, typically the "target" owns the property that's the association's end. I exploit that in this viewpoint to get the block at the end of the arrowhead of the association.

Note!

This is not meant to be an enumerated section! This area contains guidance.

If you are describing a generic pattern ("Interfaces") then domain-specific specializations should be referenced here as child pages if they have been designed and elaborated. For example, the modeling of electrical interfaces may address more concerns than are addressed by a generic connectivity pattern, but electrical interface modeling would not share a complete set of concerns with data interface modeling. In that case, domain specific pattern descriptions for electrical and data modeling should live under the generic interface definition pattern as child pages.

The domain specific example template is the same as this template. The domain-specific example may have its own submitter, line organization, point of contact, etc. The domain specific example should describe explicitly where it has redefine anything in the generic pattern, and how that is implemented in the model. The domain specific example does not have to import everything from the generic; instead, it may just describe the changes and additions that make it specific to the domain that it supports.

1.c Stereotype is applied to other elements in the base class and doesn't match any element name => remove stereotype and create new stereotypes, generalizing from <<Block>>

elements.name: Example Table
elements.documentation:
A useful method for capturing the example is a table of images and narrative:

 Example Image  Description
 You should have a model which clearly expresses all of your embedded concepts. From this model you can select views which present the application of your concepts and embedding in simple, well-paced steps. Each row entry in the table should help explain some or all of a concept. Your model views should be accompanied by narrative explaining what the viewer is meant to understand from the image, and how they can identify the significant features of your embedding. elements.name: Applicability
elements.documentation:
This section describes the problem that the pattern solves. The attributes presented here are meant to provide the pattern describer with a means to bound the scope, intended usage, and applicability of the pattern, and to allow potential users to better evaluate the merits of adopting a pattern to address their particular problem(s). Suggested Text:

To help users assess the applicability of this pattern to their work (i.e., to the problem they want to solve or their area of interest), we describe the way in which this pattern addresses a few kinds of common concerns. In particular, we address:

  • Content concerns: the kind of content users can capture in this pattern
  • Artifact concerns: the kinds of artifacts (documents and views) that can come from this pattern
  • Reasoning concerns:  the kind of reasoning (analysis) that this pattern is meant to support
  • Assumptions: what we expect to be true about the user's situation that is relevant to whether they can or should use the pattern.

The pattern describer must discuss the state (in terms of code review, etc.) of the scripts, and provide a location for which they may be obtained or viewed.

 

Required tool & plug-in versions: Please identify the required version of all the tools and plugins necessary to use the pattern. Links to the resources encouraged.

value.string:
This section contains the technical description and examples of the pattern, at the abstract ontology level and at the specific SysML level. It also describes other implementation information, such as tooling, open questions, and tricks.

Here we describe the elements that make up the pattern, their relationships, responsibilities, and collaborations. The solution does not describe a particular concrete design or implementation. Instead, the pattern provides an abstract description of a design problem and how a general arrangement of elements solves it. The solution is presented in modeling language independent terms and in its SysML embedding.

elements.name: timestamp
elements.documentation: This is the ISO 8601 timestamp indicating the last modification to the comment. It is at the resolution of seconds (ie not including milliseconds) and uses the UTC timezone with the "Z" suffix. For example: "2012-06-06T18:49:13Z".

elements.name: Model Implementation Concerns
elements.documentation:
A more practical set of concerns related to the practical aspects of modeling - model compromises that must be made in order for this to work, containment or profile concerns, etc. Resulting Context (Consequences): The results and trade-offs of applying the pattern. They may address language and modeling issues as well. The consequences include its impact on a models flexibility and extensibility.

 

An example of a model implementation concern is how the pattern is affected by use of nested ports (are there tradeoffs? is it allowed? etc.). Other examples could include when to nest classes, non-essential but helpful package structures, etc.

elements.name: showTargets

elements.name: titlePrefix

elements.name: stereotypesForPackages
elements.documentation:
Finds all packages within scope and checks/fixes if:
1.The stereotype applied matches the name of the package (can check and fix)
     Fixes:
    1.a Stereotype is not applied to any other elements in the base class => change name of stereotype to match element name
    1.b Stereotype is applied to other elements in the base class and matches an element name => create new stereotypes for all other elements
    1.c Stereotype is applied to other elements in the base class and doesn't match any element name => remove stereotype and create new stereotypes
2.The stereotype metaclass and package match (check only)

elements.name: StructuredQuery
elements.documentation: This is similar to a composite query in DocGen 2. A structured query can be defined in an activity and instanced by call behavior actions, or as a structured activity node. It is parsed like a section (except it doesn't create a section by default). This creates a new context from whatever targets are present in the current context. If loop is true, each new context is the element being looped through. When this exits, the previous context is restored.

HierarchicalPropertiesTable
elements.documentation:
A set of hierarchical tables where the rows going down depict some hierarchical organization (for example, block compositions, activity call levels), and the columns are properties such as value properties on blocks, stereotype properties, or documentation. The properties can also be hierarchical in the case of blocks.

  • If no filtered are applied, all possible properties will be discovered and displayed (does not include stereotypeProperties). This include/exclude semantics also applies to any options specific to each table type.
  • If only include filters are specified, only properties that match those filters will be displayed (and all their children properties if any).
  • If only exclude filters are specified, all properties will be displayed except for those that match the exclude filters and their hierarchical children.
  • If both include and exclude filters are specified, properties that match includes will be displayed (and their children) until the excludes match.

Because the targets for this family of tables are top level elements and most table entries are discovered, the flag loop controls whether the top level element and generated table are shown in one table or separated into different tables.

Note: complex mapping rules, such as "if a Component owns a Port that is typed by an Interface, the Component presents the Interface," are perfectly valid. 

Identify (write the name of) the stereotype that helps embed your ontology element.

Note: some ontological concepts and relationships don't have embedded stereotypes. For example, the presents relationship in the Interface Definition Pattern does not map to a discrete SysML element, so there is no stereotype to apply. 

 

Narrate the embeddings (the table is for reference). Explain any intricacies of the embedding and provide some rationale. A small section about each embedding is recommended for (i) reference; (ii) empowering the user with knowledge of your intent; (iii) transparent capture of your rationale.

value.string: Any references (papers, presentations, articles, etc.) that the pattern providers feel presents correct and relevant background, examples, or other information about the pattern. Informal references (related topics, etc.) can be added to the community page for this pattern.

elements.name: Image
elements.documentation: This produces one or more diagram images and associated titles and captions. If the targets given are images, it will print them out with the name of the diagram as the title and documentation of the diagram as captions.

elements.name: FilterByNames
elements.documentation: Given a list of regular expression patterns, include or exclude the given list of elements. (see java.util.regex.Pattern for how to use regex patterns.) (Unnamed elements will not be included regardless.)

elements.name: SortByName
elements.documentation: [Deprecated: Use Sort by Attribute] Self explanatory. (Result WILL include unnamed elements and their order is undefined) (This is superceded by SortByAttribute)

elements.name: headers
elements.documentation: Applies to certain tables where headers can be customized. As of now - CombinedMatrix and GenericTable

elements.name: systemAssociationType
elements.documentation: Optional. Specifies what kind of association to follow for hierarchical systems. 1 for composite, 2 for shared, 0 for both (default is 0).

elements.name: Organization
elements.documentation: Like JPL, LMC, etc.

elements.name: XOR
elements.documentation: Given 2 inputs of a collection of elements, outputs the symmetric difference between them.

elements.name: names
elements.documentation: List of regular expression strings. See java.util.regex.Pattern for how regex patterns work.

elements.name: First
elements.documentation: This dependency can be used from Sections, Composite Queries, or Viewpoints definitions, to a child document element. There should be at most ONE First dependency from any valid element. It indicates which query or section should be processed first under the context.

elements.name: CollectionAndFilterGroup
elements.documentation: This allows a sequence of commonly used collection/filtering actions to be grouped together as a reusable definition.

Domain-Specific Implementations/Examples
elements.documentation:
Note!

This is not meant to be an enumerated section! This area contains guidance.

If you are describing a generic pattern ("Interfaces") then domain-specific specializations should be referenced here as child pages if they have been designed and elaborated. For example, the modeling of electrical interfaces may address more concerns than are addressed by a generic connectivity pattern, but electrical interface modeling would not share a complete set of concerns with data interface modeling. In that case, domain specific pattern descriptions for electrical and data modeling should live under the generic interface definition pattern as child pages.

The domain specific example template is the same as this template. The domain-specific example may have its own submitter, line organization, point of contact, etc. The domain specific example should describe explicitly where it has redefine anything in the generic pattern, and how that is implemented in the model. The domain specific example does not have to import everything from the generic; instead, it may just describe the changes and additions that make it specific to the domain that it supports.

elements.documentation: Collect the ends of the directed relationships that are stereotyped by stereotypes indicated.
